=begin pod

=head1 09. Common Pitfalls

=head2 Overly broad schemas

B<Bad> — a single catch-all field:

=begin code :lang<raku>
token details { .* }
=end code

B<Better> — specific named fields:

=begin code :lang<raku>
token customer-email { <-[\s]>+ '@' <-[\s]>+ }
token customer-issue { '"' <( <-["]>+ )> '"' }
=end code

Broad tokens give the grammar nothing to check and make downstream code
harder to write.

=head2 Too much logic in the prompt

Put structure in the grammar — not in the prompt.

B<Fragile:>

=begin code
Extract the name, party size as an integer between 1 and 20, the time in
24-hour format, the restaurant name without articles, and the date as a
single lowercase word or ISO date…
=end code

B<Better:> write a tight grammar and tell the LLM only the DSL format and
one worked example. The grammar enforces everything else.

=head2 Ambiguous types

Prefer precise token patterns over bare C<\S+>:

=table
Vague     | Precise
\S+       | \d\d\d\d '-' \d\d '-' \d\d   (date)
\S+       | \d\d ':' \d\d                (time)
\S+       | 'low', 'medium', 'high'      (enum)
.+        | '"' <( <-["]>+ )> '"'        (quoted string)

The more specific the token, the earlier bad LLM output is caught.

=head2 Not testing the grammar standalone

Always verify the grammar parses your canonical DSL B<before> adding the LLM
step. Use the L<Slangify Playground|https://slangify.org> or a quick
C<prove6 t/01-basic.rakutest>. If the grammar itself is broken, no amount of
prompt tuning will help.

=head2 Ignoring parse failures

=begin code :lang<raku>
my $m = Grammar.parse($canonical, :actions(Actions.new));
die "Parse failed on: $canonical" unless $m;   # always check!
=end code

A silent C<Nil> match means the LLM deviated from the DSL. Log the canonical
string so you can see exactly what the LLM produced and tighten the prompt or
grammar accordingly.

=end pod
